    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2505206557" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2505206557" />
    <a title="Ms.pegasus" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/5015851-ms-pegasus"><img alt="Ms.pegasus" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1335705124p2/5015851.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2505206557?book_show_action=true">Aug 23, 2018</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Ms.pegasus" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Ms.pegasus" href="/user/show/5015851-ms-pegasus">Ms.pegasus</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



          <div>
    <span class="greyText">Recommended to Ms.pegasus by: </span>
      selection of local book club
  </div>


          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5015851-ms-pegasus?shelf=history">history</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5015851-ms-pegasus?shelf=fiction">fiction</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2505206557" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer711777739722839007">Great historical fiction immerses the reader in a different time and place. That state of immersion is shattered by glaring anachronisms. Some years ago I was watching a drama about Henry VIII. It included a dance scene that resembled a high school sock-hop more than a courtly diversion. That one scene ruined any possible sense of immersion. Writers beware: costumes and scenery alone are insufficient for creating historical fiction. <br/><br/>Unfortunately, I encountered the same problem with A COLUMN OF </span>
  <span id="freeText711777739722839007" style="display:none">Great historical fiction immerses the reader in a different time and place. That state of immersion is shattered by glaring anachronisms. Some years ago I was watching a drama about Henry VIII. It included a dance scene that resembled a high school sock-hop more than a courtly diversion. That one scene ruined any possible sense of immersion. Writers beware: costumes and scenery alone are insufficient for creating historical fiction. <br /><br />Unfortunately, I encountered the same problem with A COLUMN OF FIRE, the third of Follett's historical trilogy that began in the middle ages. David Mitchell perceptively writes that an author of historical fiction must develop a personal “Bygonese.” Follett never tries for either the language or syntax that would evoke anything other than contemporary speech. The chatty narrative at least made this 900 page behemoth a quick read.<br /><br />Anachronisms abound in this book: “Girlie” (p.130) first known use 1857 (<a target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" href="https://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/girlie);">https://www.merriam-webster.com/dicti...</a> “sexy” (p.134) first known use 1896 (<a target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" href="https://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/sexy);">https://www.merriam-webster.com/dicti...</a> “grubby” (p.135) first known use 1725 (<a target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" href="https://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/grubby">https://www.merriam-webster.com/dicti...</a>). It's a minor point but there are enough instances to cause the reader to forget that the speakers are of another time.<br /><br />The story follows the main character, Ned Willard, from 1558 to 1606. The period is filled with tumultuous events. It spans the reigns of three English monarchs and five French monarchs. (I was shocked to discover these years also spanned eight papacies. Fortunately, there's no hint of that in the book). The novel's scenes are set in England, Scotland, France, Spain and The Netherlands. More alarming, new characters kept bursting forth like the puppies in A HUNDRED AND ONE DALMATIANS. My advice is to note each character encountered in order to keep them all straight. This is particularly important for the intertwined royal and noble families of France.<br /><br />The book relies heavily on the reader's attachment to Ned. I never formed that strong attachment. I really didn't care about the Ned-Margery thread. I found the numerous secondary characters far more interesting. Ned's mother, Alice, is a shrewd merchant with interests in Calais and Seville. Ebrima is a slave working for Ned's cousin, Carlos. Both he and Carlos are forced to flee Spain. A second problem is that the characters lack dimension. Pierre and Rollo are both evil from the very beginning. <br /><br />What Follett excels at is devising suspenseful lead-ups into climactic scenes. A raid on Carlos' iron forge, numerous assassination plots, several harrowing escapes, and more than one murder keep the plot moving. Historic events like Queen Mary Stuart's execution and the St. Bartholomew's Day Massacre are mined with vivid prose. Between these episodes, however, were romantic threads that slowed the momentum of the book. Despite numerous historical details, I never felt like I was reading historical fiction.<br /><br />NOTES:<br />David Mitchell's astute essay on historical fiction:<br /><a target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" href="https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/books/bookreviews/7685510/David-Mitchell-on-Historical-Fiction.html">https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/b...</a></span>
  <a data-text-id="711777739722839007" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


